The '''Banawá''' (also '''Banawa''', '''Banavá''', '''Jafí''', '''Kitiya''', '''Banauá''') are an [[indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] group living along the [[Banawá River]] in the [[Amazonas State, Brazil]]. Their territory is between the [[Juruá River|Juruá]] and [[Purus River]]s.<ref name=pib/> Approximately 158 Banawá people live in one major village and two smaller settlements containing a single extended family each. The Banawá, who call themselves '''Kitiya''', speak [[Banawá language|Banawá]], a dialect of the [[Jamamadi language|Madi language]].

==History==
Their territory was invaded at the end of the 19th century, during the [[rubber boom]]. In the 1990s, Brazil formally recognized their land rights.<ref name=pib/>

