{{Infobox language |name=Saraveca |states=[[Bolivia]] |region=Eastern jungle |extinct=? |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern ? |fam3=[[Paresi–Waura languages|Paresí–Xingu]] |fam4=Paresí |iso3=sar |glotto=sara1331 |glottorefname=Saraveca }}
'''Saraveca''' is an extinct [[Arawakan languages|Arawakan language]] once spoken in [[Bolivia]] by the Sarave. It is said<ref>{{cite book| last = Wells| first = David| title = The Penguin Dictionary of Curious and Interesting Numbers| year = 1997| publisher = Penguin UK| isbn = 978-0-14-026149-3 }}</ref><ref>Encyclopædia Britannica, "Numerals and numeral systems".</ref> to be the only language with a [[numeral system]] based exclusively on five, although [[quinary]] systems exist. To some extent this is also an areal feature of other [[South America]]n languages; many form their numbers 6–9 as "five + one", "five + two" and so on.
